00:02:58,650 --> 00:03:02,440
So what on earth do tigers,
airplanes, and sewing machines

51
00:03:02,440 --> 00:03:04,890
have to do with cyber resilience?

52
00:03:04,890 --> 00:03:05,833
Let's find out.

53
00:03:07,670 --> 00:03:10,640
March 2020 was unforgettable.

54
00:03:10,640 --> 00:03:12,690
It brought the start of the lockdown

55
00:03:12,690 --> 00:03:15,359
and the premiere of "Tiger King".

56
00:03:15,360 --> 00:03:19,520
34 million people watched "Tiger
King" in its first 10 days.

57
00:03:19,520 --> 00:03:23,270
Eventually, 64 million
households would tune in.

58
00:03:23,270 --> 00:03:26,750
That's an incredible surge,
and it got me thinking:

59
00:03:26,750 --> 00:03:30,970
how does Netflix ensure that
its 203 million subscribers

60
00:03:30,970 --> 00:03:34,453
can stream whatever they
want whenever they want it?

61
00:03:35,480 --> 00:03:37,730
Netflix does not fall down often:

62
00:03:37,730 --> 00:03:39,822
less than 30 seconds a week.

63
00:03:40,770 --> 00:03:44,080
In 2011, Netflix was
preparing to move its content

64
00:03:44,080 --> 00:03:46,200
from the data center to the cloud.

65
00:03:46,200 --> 00:03:48,410
The new availability and performance

66
00:03:48,410 --> 00:03:50,630
were critical to user experience,

67
00:03:50,630 --> 00:03:53,780
and they had to design a
fault-tolerant architecture

68
00:03:53,780 --> 00:03:56,760
within an environment
they didn't fully control.

69
00:03:56,760 --> 00:04:00,340
So they invented something
called Chaos Monkey.

70
00:04:00,340 --> 00:04:03,420
Imagine a monkey shutting
down production instances

71
00:04:03,420 --> 00:04:05,833
and chewing through cables
in your data center.

72
00:04:06,990 --> 00:04:09,120
By bringing in and building in chaos,

73
00:04:09,120 --> 00:04:12,050
this tool accounted for
a common type of failure

74
00:04:12,050 --> 00:04:16,209
and ensured graceful
degradation and survival

75
00:04:16,209 --> 00:04:18,349
without any customer impact.

76
00:04:18,350 --> 00:04:21,680
In fact, simulating chaos worked so well,

77
00:04:21,680 --> 00:04:25,860
it inspired the creation
of the Netflix Simian Army,

78
00:04:25,860 --> 00:04:28,770
a collection of tools to
help prepare for chaos:

79
00:04:28,770 --> 00:04:31,530
the latency monkey, conformity monkey,

80
00:04:31,530 --> 00:04:34,989
and, yes, for sure, security monkey.

81
00:04:34,990 --> 00:04:37,640
It's that kind of engineering
that has helped Netflix

82
00:04:37,640 --> 00:04:40,050
build a resilient and successful business,

83
00:04:40,050 --> 00:04:43,010
and ensured we could
all binge "Tiger King".

84
00:04:43,010 --> 00:04:45,300
Chaos is a pretty good way

85
00:04:45,300 --> 00:04:47,923
to describe our context in cybersecurity:

86
00:04:49,060 --> 00:04:51,280
boundless, complex, hyper-connected

87
00:04:51,280 --> 00:04:55,429
and dynamic tech stacks
sitting on multiple clouds;

88
00:04:55,430 --> 00:04:57,763
workloads that move about everywhere;

89
00:04:58,640 --> 00:05:00,840
machine and human actors working,

90
00:05:00,840 --> 00:05:03,070
playing, learning from anywhere;

91
00:05:03,070 --> 00:05:05,930
and the added randomness
of malicious actors

92
00:05:05,930 --> 00:05:09,920
trying to disrupt, steal,
subvert, and instill fear.

93
00:05:09,920 --> 00:05:11,910
How can you secure chaos?

94
00:05:11,910 --> 00:05:13,790
You can't, you don't.

95
00:05:13,790 --> 00:05:17,750
You focus on resilience
by embracing chaos.

96
00:05:17,750 --> 00:05:19,320
How?

97
00:05:19,320 --> 00:05:24,320
One, expect the unexpected;
two, trust no one;

98
00:05:26,240 --> 00:05:29,940
and three, compartmentalize failure zones.

99
00:05:29,940 --> 00:05:32,390
In cybersecurity, to practice chaos

100
00:05:32,390 --> 00:05:34,140
and reliability engineering,

101
00:05:34,140 --> 00:05:37,669
teams should constantly assess
and test their responses.

102
00:05:37,670 --> 00:05:40,830
Attack your own network and see
if you recorded that attack,

103
00:05:40,830 --> 00:05:43,099
because if you don't have visibility,

104
00:05:43,100 --> 00:05:45,250
then you don't know what to defend.

105
00:05:45,250 --> 00:05:47,200
And once you do have visibility,

106
00:05:47,200 --> 00:05:49,430
use threat intelligence to understand

107
00:05:49,430 --> 00:05:52,050
your vertical's likeliest antagonists,

108
00:05:52,050 --> 00:05:54,130
including their methods.

109
00:05:54,130 --> 00:05:57,510
And then in addition to
modeling the likeliest attack,

110
00:05:57,510 --> 00:06:00,590
make sure to throw in a few unlikely ones

111
00:06:00,590 --> 00:06:02,722
in your red and blue team exercise.

112
00:06:03,720 --> 00:06:07,230
Zero trust was always important,

113
00:06:07,230 --> 00:06:10,450
but in the post-COVID
work-from-anywhere-always world,

114
00:06:10,450 --> 00:06:11,890
it is an imperative.

115
00:06:11,890 --> 00:06:15,729
It is a mindset, not just an architecture.

116
00:06:15,730 --> 00:06:19,530
Micro-segmentation, providing
layer seven threat prevention,

117
00:06:19,530 --> 00:06:23,549
and risk-based continuous
multifactor authentication

118
00:06:23,550 --> 00:06:27,860
are critical components,
but most important of all

119
00:06:27,860 --> 00:06:32,310
is to limit trust to what
is absolutely required

120
00:06:32,310 --> 00:06:37,090
and never elevate trust
based on unreliable factors.

121
00:06:37,090 --> 00:06:40,229
The global system for mobile
communications predicts

122
00:06:40,230 --> 00:06:42,280
that IoT connections will reach

123
00:06:42,280 --> 00:06:46,190
almost 25 billion globally by 2025,

124
00:06:46,190 --> 00:06:47,980
and that might be an underestimation

125
00:06:47,980 --> 00:06:50,360
based on the traction of 5G.

126
00:06:50,360 --> 00:06:54,100
By some estimates, we are
connecting 127 devices

127
00:06:54,100 --> 00:06:57,330
to the internet every second.

128
00:06:57,330 --> 00:06:59,479
And it's not just connected devices,

129
00:06:59,480 --> 00:07:01,210
it's connected organizations

130
00:07:01,210 --> 00:07:04,210
and the private data flowing
through this value chain.

131
00:07:04,210 --> 00:07:07,719
Companies increasingly
rely on third parties

132
00:07:07,720 --> 00:07:11,130
and on average share confidential
and sensitive information

133
00:07:11,130 --> 00:07:15,430
with approximately 583 third parties.

134
00:07:15,430 --> 00:07:19,120
Yet only a third keep a
comprehensive inventory

135
00:07:19,120 --> 00:07:21,290
of these third parties.

136
00:07:21,290 --> 00:07:25,830
Too many dominoes stacked
too tightly together.

137
00:07:25,830 --> 00:07:29,870
Look, we can ensure that
each domino remains upright.

138
00:07:29,870 --> 00:07:33,080
Instead, we have to
space them farther apart.

139
00:07:33,080 --> 00:07:34,460
What does that mean?

140
00:07:34,460 --> 00:07:37,030
Implement third party risk assessments

141
00:07:37,030 --> 00:07:39,729
to map your organizational business graph

142
00:07:39,730 --> 00:07:42,360
to get a vectorized view of risk.

143
00:07:42,360 --> 00:07:45,870
Implement network segmentation
and least privilege

144
00:07:45,870 --> 00:07:50,100
not just in east-west scenarios
or southbound traffic,

145
00:07:50,100 --> 00:07:52,240
but northbound as well.

146
00:07:52,240 --> 00:07:54,330
It's like wearing a mask.

147
00:07:54,330 --> 00:07:57,280
We should wear one not
just to protect ourselves,

148
00:07:57,280 --> 00:07:58,852
but to protect others.

149
00:07:59,810 --> 00:08:02,340
What if the SolarWinds servers

150
00:08:02,340 --> 00:08:04,880
were only allowed to
talk to the known good,

151
00:08:04,880 --> 00:08:08,450
rather than being disallowed
to connect to the known bad?

152
00:08:08,450 --> 00:08:10,400
Could the Twitter hack have been avoided

153
00:08:10,400 --> 00:08:12,409
if the employees had not been trusted

154
00:08:12,410 --> 00:08:15,520
to change the email addresses of accounts?

155
00:08:15,520 --> 00:08:20,282
By being prepared for chaos,
we will fall less often.

156
00:08:21,190 --> 00:08:22,969
But despite our best efforts,

157
00:08:22,970 --> 00:08:25,750
at some point along our
journey, the terrain will shift,

158
00:08:25,750 --> 00:08:28,883
the ground will catch our
feet, and we will stumble.

159
00:08:29,780 --> 00:08:33,332
This next section is about
withstanding the fall.

160
00:08:35,039 --> 00:08:37,039
In World War Two, the Allies faced

161
00:08:37,039 --> 00:08:38,849
a version of this problem.

162
00:08:38,850 --> 00:08:41,990
They needed to minimize
damage to their aircraft

163
00:08:41,990 --> 00:08:44,169
in order to keep them flying.

164
00:08:44,169 --> 00:08:45,689
They worked with a statistician

165
00:08:45,690 --> 00:08:48,730
named Abraham Wald from
Columbia University

166
00:08:48,730 --> 00:08:50,500
who examined damaged aircraft

167
00:08:50,500 --> 00:08:52,690
that had returned from missions.

168
00:08:52,690 --> 00:08:54,650
He saw where the bullets had hit,

169
00:08:54,650 --> 00:08:56,699
and used those patterns to recommend

170
00:08:56,700 --> 00:08:59,783
where engineers should
place additional armor.

171
00:09:00,660 --> 00:09:03,550
Before Wald, the military assumed

172
00:09:03,550 --> 00:09:07,303
that they should reinforce the
areas drawing the most fire.

173
00:09:08,340 --> 00:09:10,020
But after looking at the damage,

174
00:09:10,020 --> 00:09:13,470
Wald made a counterintuitive
recommendation:

175
00:09:13,470 --> 00:09:15,830
place the extra armor in the areas

176
00:09:15,830 --> 00:09:18,400
that showed the least damage.

177
00:09:18,400 --> 00:09:19,550
Why?

178
00:09:19,550 --> 00:09:23,390
The aircraft that Wald
examined may have been damaged,

179
00:09:23,390 --> 00:09:25,560
but had returned safely to base.

180
00:09:25,560 --> 00:09:27,560
The unscarred areas had been enough

181
00:09:27,560 --> 00:09:29,233
to carry the plane back home.

182
00:09:30,180 --> 00:09:34,640
Wald's remarkable insight bears
an important lesson for us.

183
00:09:34,640 --> 00:09:36,490
Today, we are confronted

184
00:09:36,490 --> 00:09:39,260
with a modern version of Wald's problem:

185
00:09:39,260 --> 00:09:41,600
there's only so much armor to go around,

186
00:09:41,600 --> 00:09:44,590
and too much armor can slow us down.

187
00:09:44,590 --> 00:09:47,600
We are all working with limited resources,

188
00:09:47,600 --> 00:09:50,600
so we have to prioritize intelligently.

189
00:09:50,600 --> 00:09:52,130
We have to protect the areas

190
00:09:52,130 --> 00:09:54,730
that represent the greatest risks,

191
00:09:54,730 --> 00:09:57,260
not where we see the most holes.

192
00:09:57,260 --> 00:10:01,030
NIST Cybersecurity Framework
does an excellent job

193
00:10:01,030 --> 00:10:04,470
of proposing a risk-based
approach to cyber.

194
00:10:04,470 --> 00:10:07,050
Here is what DHS Secretary Mayorkas

195
00:10:07,050 --> 00:10:09,900
had to say about resilience.

196
00:10:09,900 --> 00:10:13,510
- Pursuing cyber resilience
requires a third principle,

197
00:10:13,510 --> 00:10:17,300
namely a focus on a risk-based approach.

198
00:10:17,300 --> 00:10:19,560
Determining what risks to prioritize

199
00:10:19,560 --> 00:10:22,050
and how to allocate limited resources

200
00:10:22,050 --> 00:10:25,113
is crucial to maximizing
the government's impact.

201
00:10:25,960 --> 00:10:28,840
- The US government faces
many cyber missions,

202
00:10:28,840 --> 00:10:31,370
and in 2020, CISA ascertained

203
00:10:31,370 --> 00:10:33,600
that the US presidential election

204
00:10:33,600 --> 00:10:35,710
was foundational to our democracy

205
00:10:35,710 --> 00:10:38,290
and we needed to put more armor there.

206
00:10:38,290 --> 00:10:40,780
By prioritizing it, CISA protected

207
00:10:40,780 --> 00:10:43,089
the cyber aspects of the election.

208
00:10:43,090 --> 00:10:46,090
Every organization, not
just the federal government,

209
00:10:46,090 --> 00:10:49,490
needs to deploy an integrated
risk management solution,

210
00:10:49,490 --> 00:10:53,150
and implement methods
to quantify all risk,

211
00:10:53,150 --> 00:10:55,290
including cyber risk.

212
00:10:55,290 --> 00:10:57,980
Since the cyber onslaught is unrelenting,

213
00:10:57,980 --> 00:11:00,160
