00:13:29,170 --> 00:13:31,683
and wider representation than ever before.

261
00:13:32,690 --> 00:13:34,700
We seek your continued engagement

262
00:13:35,755 --> 00:13:39,320
as we reimagine the conference
for the post-COVID world

263
00:13:39,320 --> 00:13:41,843
with hybrid events and a year-round model.

264
00:13:42,690 --> 00:13:45,290
Today, I also implore us to consider

265
00:13:45,290 --> 00:13:47,563
another idea to grow our community.

266
00:13:48,690 --> 00:13:51,510
This is Marcus Hutchins.

267
00:13:51,510 --> 00:13:54,420
When he was nine, Marcus took
apart his family's computer

268
00:13:54,420 --> 00:13:56,750
and the code that operated it.

269
00:13:56,750 --> 00:13:59,730
At 14, he created a password stealer.

270
00:13:59,730 --> 00:14:04,680
At 15, he ran a botnet of more
than 8,000 hacked computers.

271
00:14:04,680 --> 00:14:07,800
And then in 2017, he was the individual

272
00:14:07,800 --> 00:14:10,729
that found the kill switch
for the WannaCry worm,

273
00:14:10,730 --> 00:14:12,450
saving the internet.

274
00:14:12,450 --> 00:14:16,000
It wasn't a straight and
narrow path for Marcus,

275
00:14:16,000 --> 00:14:17,740
though he eventually worked his way

276
00:14:17,740 --> 00:14:20,173
into a legitimate cybersecurity carrier.

277
00:14:21,080 --> 00:14:25,200
He was on the dark side,
but became a gray hatter.

278
00:14:25,200 --> 00:14:28,810
In 2017, he was arrested and faced a trial

279
00:14:28,810 --> 00:14:30,979
for his past misdeeds.

280
00:14:30,980 --> 00:14:33,090
The judge's lenient sentence

281
00:14:33,090 --> 00:14:36,290
acknowledged his remarkable contribution.

282
00:14:36,290 --> 00:14:40,390
This was an act of inclusion
and profound wisdom

283
00:14:40,390 --> 00:14:42,850
that shows us that we need to find a way

284
00:14:42,850 --> 00:14:45,130
to never give up on bright minds

285
00:14:45,130 --> 00:14:47,433
and attract them into our community.

286
00:14:48,440 --> 00:14:51,853
We need to recruit better
than the adversary.

287
00:14:53,360 --> 00:14:55,880
Our community has shown
remarkable solidarity

288
00:14:55,880 --> 00:14:57,650
when one of us falls.

289
00:14:57,650 --> 00:15:00,380
We may have competition
within the community,

290
00:15:00,380 --> 00:15:02,730
but we have each other's back.

291
00:15:02,730 --> 00:15:04,850
We are getting better
at sharing and learning,

292
00:15:04,850 --> 00:15:08,890
so when one of us falls, all of us learn.

293
00:15:08,890 --> 00:15:11,400
We all rise up stronger.

294
00:15:11,400 --> 00:15:13,850
In 2020, we saw cyber incidents

295
00:15:13,850 --> 00:15:17,090
of unprecedented scale and scope.

296
00:15:17,090 --> 00:15:21,560
But let's note that we
have not yet encountered

297
00:15:21,560 --> 00:15:24,430
a global cyber pandemic.

298
00:15:24,430 --> 00:15:26,790
Hard as our journey may seem,

299
00:15:26,790 --> 00:15:31,540
we have not been fully tested
yet, and must remain vigilant.

300
00:15:31,540 --> 00:15:34,219
The next leg of a long
journey is just beginning.

301
00:15:34,220 --> 00:15:37,660
There will certainly be
challenges, stumbles, and failures.

302
00:15:37,660 --> 00:15:39,870
But I hope that these three examples

303
00:15:39,870 --> 00:15:41,570
and the stories behind them

304
00:15:41,570 --> 00:15:44,000
will inspire us to go the distance.

305
00:15:44,000 --> 00:15:48,990
We can do so by preparing for
chaos, prioritizing smartly,

306
00:15:48,990 --> 00:15:51,800
and leveraging the power of our community.

307
00:15:51,800 --> 00:15:56,089
Tigers, airplanes, sewing machines.

308
00:15:56,090 --> 00:15:58,770
And if we do so, we will fall less often,

309
00:15:58,770 --> 00:16:02,370
withstand the fall when we
do, and rise up stronger.

310
00:16:02,370 --> 00:16:04,773
We will get better at resilience.

311
00:16:05,780 --> 00:16:07,949
So let me leave you with one last image

312
00:16:07,950 --> 00:16:10,100
to carry on your journey.

313
00:16:10,100 --> 00:16:14,910
Kintsugi is Japanese for
golden seams or golden repair.

314
00:16:14,910 --> 00:16:17,760
It is the art of using
gold lacquers and resins

315
00:16:17,760 --> 00:16:21,470
to restore broken pottery and ceramics.

316
00:16:21,470 --> 00:16:25,630
But kintsugi does more than
restore, it transforms.

317
00:16:25,630 --> 00:16:29,253
It doesn't hide falls and
breaks, it highlights them.

318
00:16:30,170 --> 00:16:32,920
The golden wound becomes a celebration

319
00:16:32,920 --> 00:16:35,540
of the hands that put
things back together,

320
00:16:35,540 --> 00:16:38,130
a celebration of the purposefulness

321
00:16:38,130 --> 00:16:40,340
and learning from the process,

322
00:16:40,340 --> 00:16:43,560
a celebration of resilience.

323
00:16:43,560 --> 00:16:46,900
So friends, take some time this week

324
00:16:46,900 --> 00:16:49,853
to celebrate our resilient journey.

325
00:16:51,150 --> 00:16:53,319
Continue to believe in the light

326
00:16:53,320 --> 00:16:56,340
even if we can't see it sometimes.

327
00:16:56,340 --> 00:16:58,750
Continue to be the light.

328
00:16:58,750 --> 00:16:59,650
Thank you.

